<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="3" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[192,1440,512,761]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,335,512,536]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Females of this species group are identified by a unique combination of characters: head unarmed posterolaterally; mesonotum rounded laterally, lacking longitudinal medial carina; scutellar scale distinct, connected to anterior transverse carina; apex of middle and hind femora truncate; 
<collectionCode box="[1408,1426,577,601]" name="Tavera, Department of Geology and Geophysics" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">T</collectionCode>
2 having four integumental spots; gena carinate; pygidium broadly ovate. Males can be diagnosed by having the parameres conspicuously sinuous, with an isolated medial tuft of long setae ventrally; cuspis virtually straight and overall asetose, except for a small tuft of short setae apically. External characters include white meso- and metatibial spurs, truncate axilla, mesopleuron with blunt tubercle; hypopygium trapezoidal and 
<collectionCode box="[391,410,737,761]" name="Tavera, Department of Geology and Geophysics" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">T</collectionCode>
3–5 entirely clothed with white setae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[192,1014,785,809]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
<paragraph blockId="4.[192,1014,785,809]" box="[192,1014,785,809]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,408,785,809]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Included taxon.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="(Gerstaecker, 1874)" baseAuthorityName="Gerstaecker" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[415,1011,785,809]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Traumatomutilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vitelligera">
<emphasis box="[415,759,785,809]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Traumatomutilla vitelligera</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Gerstaecker, A." box="[775,1002,785,809]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="299 - 328" refId="ref18911" refString="Gerstaecker, A. 1874. Mutillarum Americae meridionalis indigenarum synopsis systematica et synonymica. Archiv fur Naturgeschichte 40 (1): 41 - 77, 299 - 328." type="journal article" year="1874">Gerstaecker, 1874</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="3" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[192,1440,833,889]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,371,833,857]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Distribution.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Gerstaecker" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[378,722,833,857]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Traumatomutilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vitelligera">
<emphasis box="[378,722,833,857]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Traumatomutilla vitelligera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been recorded from six South American countries, but we have seen specimens only from semiarid regions of 
<collectingCountry box="[860,965,865,889]" name="Ecuador" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[977,1036,866,889]" name="Peru" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Peru</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1096,1165,865,889]" name="Chile" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Chile</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="3" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[192,1440,913,1194]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,322,913,937]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Remarks.</emphasis>
The vitelligera group is one of the three species groups of 
<emphasis box="[1007,1219,913,937]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Traumatomutilla</emphasis>
with only one species, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Gerstaecker, 1874)" baseAuthorityName="Gerstaecker" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[251,655,945,969]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Traumatomutilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vitelligera">
<emphasis box="[251,406,945,969]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">T. vitelligera</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Gerstaecker, A." box="[421,647,945,969]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="299 - 328" refId="ref18911" refString="Gerstaecker, A. 1874. Mutillarum Americae meridionalis indigenarum synopsis systematica et synonymica. Archiv fur Naturgeschichte 40 (1): 41 - 77, 299 - 328." type="journal article" year="1874">Gerstaecker, 1874</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. As in 
<taxonomicName authority="(Gerstaecker, 1874)" baseAuthorityName="Gerstaecker" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[734,1127,945,969]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Traumatomutilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diabolica">
<emphasis box="[734,879,945,969]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">T. diabolica</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Gerstaecker, A." box="[893,1118,945,969]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="299 - 328" refId="ref18911" refString="Gerstaecker, A. 1874. Mutillarum Americae meridionalis indigenarum synopsis systematica et synonymica. Archiv fur Naturgeschichte 40 (1): 41 - 77, 299 - 328." type="journal article" year="1874">Gerstaecker, 1874</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, the mesosomal sculpture of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Gerstaecker" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[220,374,977,1001]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Traumatomutilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vitelligera">
<emphasis box="[220,374,977,1001]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">T. vitelligera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from other large-bodied 
<emphasis box="[756,970,977,1001]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Traumatomutilla</emphasis>
by lacking the distinctive structures of the more diverse, large-bodied species groups [medial longitudinal mesonotal carina (indica), bilobate anterior transverse carina separated from scutellar scale (juvenilis), and lateral mesonotal tubercles (quadrinotata)]. The 
<typeStatus box="[453,563,1074,1098]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">lectotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Gerstaecker" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[604,762,1073,1097]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Traumatomutilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vitelligera">
<emphasis box="[604,762,1073,1097]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">T. vitelligera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, however, has a conspicuous scutellar scale connected laterally with its anterolateral carinae, as in many species of the indica group. Additionally, aside from a few species found in northwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[635,754,1138,1162]" name="Colombia" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, this is the only species in 
<emphasis box="[1075,1289,1137,1161]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Traumatomutilla</emphasis>
known west of the Andes.
</paragraph>
